•	Statistics-related functions (mean, std, distance computations)
•	Plotting utilities (plot, bar, figure, axes)
No proprietary external libraries are required beyond standard MATLAB functionality.

Methodology
The computational model follows a structured analytical pipeline:
1. Similarity Modeling
Pairwise Euclidean distances are computed among patient records to identify nearest neighbors. This stage quantifies structural proximity between instances based on recorded attributes.
2. Neighborhood Formation
For each record, the closest neighboring instances are selected. These neighbors represent clinically similar patients whose data contribute to inference.
3. Normalization
Record values are mean-centered to remove systematic bias and enhance comparative stability during similarity assessment.
4. Collaborative Filtering
Predicted values are estimated using similarity-weighted aggregation. This mechanism emulates knowledge transfer from related patient cases.
5. Error Estimation
Prediction accuracy is quantified using Mean Absolute Error (MAE), reflecting deviation between observed and estimated values.
6. Classification
Supervised classifiers (KNN, Decision Tree, Naïve Bayes, Neural Networks) are employed to evaluate diagnostic consistency and predictive reliability.
7. Visualization
Performance metrics and error distributions are visualized to facilitate interpretability and comparative analysis.

Assessment Metrics
Model performance is evaluated using widely accepted diagnostic metrics:
•	Accuracy – Measures overall correctness of predictions
•	Recall (Sensitivity) – Assesses detection capability for positive instances
•	Precision – Quantifies reliability of positive predictions
•	F-measure – Harmonic balance of precision and recall
These metrics provide complementary perspectives on classification behavior, particularly relevant in medical datasets where class imbalance and misclassification costs are critical considerations.

Related Publication
Nanehkaran, Y., Licai, Z., Chen, J., Zhongpan, Q., Xiaofeng, Y., Dorostkar Navaei, Y., & Einy, S.
Diagnosis of chronic diseases based on patients’ health records in IoT healthcare using the recommender system. Wireless Communications and Mobile Computing, 2022(1), 5663001.
DOI: 10.1155/2022/5663001

Summary of the Associated Study
The referenced study proposes a medical recommender framework for chronic disease management in IoT-enabled healthcare systems. The approach combines K-Nearest Neighbor classification for disease identification with collaborative filtering for treatment recommendation. Patient similarity derived from clinical symptoms and recorded attributes constitutes the central mechanism for inference. Experimental evaluation demonstrates that similarity-based reasoning can effectively support diagnostic decision-making and treatment suggestion, yielding improved predictive performance relative to conventional techniques. The study underscores the potential of recommender system paradigms in personalized digital healthcare environments.

Materials & Methods – Computing Infrastructure
All computational experiments were conducted under the following configuration:
•	Hardware: Laptop ASUS N56J, Intel Core i7, 8 GB RAM
•	Operating System: Windows 10 (64-bit)
•	Software: MATLAB R2021b

Conclusions
The implementation illustrates the feasibility of integrating similarity-based learning and collaborative recommendation for chronic disease diagnosis and treatment support. The results reinforce the relevance of recommender system methodologies within clinical decision-support contexts, particularly for data-rich IoT healthcare ecosystems.

Limitations
Several methodological considerations should be acknowledged:
•	Dependence on dataset structure and quality
•	Sensitivity to similarity measures and neighborhood size
•	Simplified handling of missing or noisy records
•	Absence of direct clinical validation
Future investigations may consider robust normalization strategies, adaptive similarity metrics, and validation using heterogeneous clinical datasets.

